Creating additive parts requires intense iterative design, meaning we assess and adjust over and over again. That's why we almost always print plastic prototypes first‚Äìso we can visualize our designs quickly and without the cost and resources of metal printing.

I‚Äôm Laura, general manager of Women‚Äôs Health & X-Ray in Europe at @GEHealthcare, and I‚Äôm all about improving the patient experience. When we introduced our mammography device around the globe, it was important our work didn‚Äôt end there.

When developing Senographe Pristina and Pristina Dueta, we didn't just want to create great mammography devices in theory. We wanted women to actually feel more comfortable and confident during an exam. That's why patient feedback was such a crucial part of our process.

Our main goal in developing Senographe Pristina was to change the perception of mammography. We wanted women to feel empowered üí™, not afraid. Being an active participant during an exam with the Pristina Dueta helps with that. My friend Camille can tell you all about it.

One reason women avoid mammograms is fear of potential pain. So we decided to give women a better sense of control with Pristina Dueta‚Äîthe first-ever patient-assisted compression device. With the help of a technologist, women can set the compression that feels right to them.

Did you know that many women avoid getting a mammogram out of fear? That‚Äôs why we designed the SensorySuite, an interactive experience that can help reduce anxiety and takes the "medical" feel out of the mammography process.

We're always searching for ways to help radiologists diagnose easier and more accurately. That‚Äôs how Contrast Enhanced Spectral Mammography (CESM) came about. It can help reduce image noise and provide contrast so that radiologists can better pinpoint lesions üîé.

Here is the Image Review Lab, where Karima is showing us scans taken with Pristina. On the left, we have a 3D image that we then break down into several 2D images, like on the right. This allows doctors to see more angles in the breast, which can help better diagnose patients.

Time to suit up! We have to wear these any time we go into the clean lab, which is where we build our x-ray tubes. These fun little suits prevent outside contaminants from dirtying up the tubes and creating foreign artifacts on imaging. Clean tubes can generate cleaner images.

One of the many things we do in the clean lab is tig weld our X-ray tubes. This machine welds quickly and precisely, which can help ensure the equipment inside the mammography machine is high quality and provides clear imaging for technologists. Only the best for Pristina!

Welcome to the anechoic chamber. It may look strange, but it‚Äôs actually very important. The conical padding you see here is designed to completely absorb sound & electromagnetic waves so that we can test Pristina without any interference from the environment or other machines. üì°

Who knew making X-ray tubes could be so beautiful? üòç Our glass-blowing technique has developed quite a bit from the first one ever created by Wilhelm Roentgen in 1865. Fun fact: he actually named them ‚ÄúX‚Äù rays for their unknown properties at the time.
